''[[Coco (2017 film)|Coco]]'' is a 2017 American [[3D film|3D]] [[computer-animated]] [[fantasy film|fantasy]] film produced by [[Pixar Animation Studios]] and released by [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. The film was directed by [[Lee Unkrich]] and was based on an original idea by Unkrich with the screenplay written by [[Adrian Molina]] (who also co-directed) and Matthew Aldrich. The film follows Miguel Rivera (voiced by [[Anthony Gonzalez (actor)|Anthony Gonzalez]]), a 12-year-old boy, who is accidentally transported to the land of the dead. There he seeks the help of his deceased musician great-great-grandfather to return him to his family among the living. The film's voice cast also stars [[Gael García Bernal]], [[Benjamin Bratt]], [[Alanna Ubach]], [[Renée Victor]], [[Ana Ofelia Murguía]], and [[Edward James Olmos]].<ref name="PressKit" />

The film premiered at the [[Morelia International Film Festival]] on October 20, 2017. It was theatrically released in Mexico the following week,<ref name="MexicoRelease" /> before being released in over 3,900 theatres in the United States and Canada on November 27.<ref name="USCanadaRelease" /> {{As of|2018|8|7|df=US}}, ''Coco'' has grossed $807.1 million at the worldwide box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pixar1117.htm|title=Coco (2017)|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=August 7, 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180807201313/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pixar1117.htm|archivedate=August 7, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]], a [[review aggregator]], surveyed 276 reviews and judged 97% of them to be positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/coco_2017|title=Coco (2017)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=June 14, 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617035244/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/coco_2017|archivedate=June 17, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] calculated a [[weighted average]] score of 81 out of 100 based on 48 reviews, indicating "universal acclaim".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/coco-2017|title=Coco reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 11, 2018|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617035327/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/coco-2017|archivedate=June 17, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>

''Coco'' garnered a variety of awards and nominations, many of them in the Best Animated Feature and Best Original Song (for "[[Remember Me (Pixar song)|Remember Me]]") categories. It was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]] as the [[National Board of Review Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film of 2017]]. At the [[90th Academy Awards]], it won [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]]. The film garnered two nominations at the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]], winning for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film|Best Animated Feature Film]]. ''Coco'' also won the [[BAFTA Award for Best Animated Film]] and the Critics' Choice Movie Award for both [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]] and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Song|Best Song]]. The film led the [[45th Annie Awards]] with thirteen nominations, and won a record-breaking eleven awards,<ref name="AnnieRecord" /> including [[Annie Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]], [[Annie Award for Directing in a Feature Production|Outstanding Achievement for Directing in an Animated Feature Production]], [[Annie Award for Writing in a Feature Production|Outstanding Achievement for Writing in an Animated Feature Production]], and [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Outstanding Achievement for Voice Acting in an Animated Feature Production]] for Gonzalez. Producer [[Darla K. Anderson]] won [[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Animated Motion Picture|Outstanding Producer of Animated Theatrical Motion Pictures]] at the [[Producers Guild of America Awards 2017|29th Producers Guild of America Awards]]. The film won two [[Saturn Award]]s for [[Saturn Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]] and [[Saturn Award for Best Music|Best Music]]. The film's visual effects were acclaimed by the [[Visual Effects Society]], which gave the film awards in all four of its animated film categories.

