{{Infobox body of water | name = Strait of Bonifacio | native_name = | native_name_lang = | other_name = | image = | alt = | caption = | image_bathymetry = | alt_bathymetry = | caption_bathymetry = | location = [[Mediterranean Sea]] | group = | coordinates = {{coord|41|18|43|N|9|12|46|E|type:waterbody|display=title,inline}} | type =[[Strait]] | etymology = | part_of = | inflow = | rivers = | outflow = | oceans = | catchment = | basin_countries ={{flag|France}} {{flag|Italy}} | agency = | designation = | date-built = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} For man-made and other recent bodies of water --> | engineer = | date-flooded = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} For man-made and other recent bodies of water --> | length = | min_width ={{conv|11|km|mi}} | area = | depth = | max-depth ={{conv|100|m|ft}} | volume = | residence_time = | salinity = | shore = | elevation = | temperature_high = | temperature_low = | frozen = | islands = | islands_category = | sections = | trenches = | benches = | cities =[[Bonifacio, Corse-du-Sud|Bonifacio]] | pushpin_map =Mediterranean#France#Italy | pushpin_label_position = <!-- left, right, top or bottom --> | pushpin_map_alt = | pushpin_map_caption = | website = | reference = }}
The '''Strait of Bonifacio''' ({{lang-lat|Fretum Gallicum}}, {{lang-fr|Bouches de Bonifacio}}, {{lang-it|Bocche di Bonifacio}}, {{lang-co|Bucchi di Bunifaziu}}, [[Gallurese language|Gallurese]]: ''Bocchi di Bunifaciu'', {{lang-sc|Buccas de Bonifatziu}}, {{lang-lij|Bocche de Bunifazziu}}) is the [[strait]] between [[Corsica]] and [[Sardinia]], named after the Corsican town [[Bonifacio, Corse-du-Sud|Bonifacio]]. It is {{convert|11|km|mi|abbr=on}} wide <ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.esa.int/esaEO/SEM7FTZ57NG_index_0.html |title= European Space Agency Observing the Earth |work=web page |publisher= European Space Agency |accessdate =4 October 2011}}</ref> and divides the [[Tyrrhenian Sea]] from the western [[Mediterranean Sea]]. The strait is notorious among [[sailor]]s for its [[weather]], [[ocean current|currents]], [[shoal]]s, and other obstacles.
The most famous disaster in the Strait of Bonifacio was that of the [[France|French]] [[frigate]] ''[[French frigate Sémillante (1841)|Sémillante]]'' on February 15, 1855. ''Sémillante'' had left the port of [[Toulon]] the day before on its way into the [[Black Sea]] to supply the [[Crimean War]] with troops. A storm caused it to hit a reef; the ship sank and none of the 750 soldiers on board survived.
After a [[tanker (ship)|tanker]] disaster in 1993, the passage through the Strait of Bonifacio has been prohibited for French and Italian flag ships with [[dangerous goods]]. Passage for ships with dangerous goods sailing under other flags is strongly discouraged and subject to mandatory piloting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://iucn.org/about/union/secretariat/offices/iucnmed/iucn_med_programme/marine_programme/governance/glossary/?11352 |title=The Strait of Bonifacio: a Particularly Sensitive Sea Area (PSSA) |accessdate=18 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imo.org/blast/blastDataHelper.asp?data_id=23312&filename=A766(18).pdf |title=IMO Resolution A.666(18) Navigation in the Strait of Bonifacio |accessdate=18 June 2013 |work=PDF document}}</ref>
Its maximum depth is {{convert|100|m|ft}}.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ram.minambiente.it/documents/Altri%20atti/Bocche%20di%20Bonifacio%20-%20proposta%20di%20designazione%20di%20una%20PSSA/MEPC_61-9%20del%2025%20giugno%202010.pdf |title= International Maritime Organization Marine Environment Protection Committee 61st Session, Agenda Item 9 Annex, page 1 |work=PDF document |publisher= International Maritime Organization |accessdate =4 October 2011}}</ref>
==Gallery== <gallery caption="Strait of Bonifacio" mode=packed style="font-size:88%; line-height:130%" heights=150> File:Strait of bonifacio2.jpg|Location of the Strait. File:Bouches de Bonifacio.JPG|The Strait as seen from [[Santa Teresa di Gallura]] in Sardinia; Corsica is in the background. File:Strait of Bonifacio.jpg|The Strait as seen from the northernmost tip of Sardinia; the southern coast of Corsica is barely visible. File:Scogliere bocche di bonifacio.JPG|The Strait as seen from the Corsican coast. File:Strasse von Bonifacio.jpg|The Strait as seen from above the ground. </gallery>
